export const voiceSamples: { label: string; text: string }[] = [
  {
    label: "On the throughline of the projects",
    text:
      "The projects are not as scattered as they look. Hivemind, Purposeless Efficiency, and Theseus all sit on a single throughline: the production of structure where the dominant institutions produce noise. Each one picks a different surface — analytical software, written argument, a personal knowledge system — and refuses, in its own register, the standard pretense that the absence of structure is somehow a form of openness. It is not. It is illegibility, sold as humility, defended as flexibility, and almost always paid for by the operator who is trying to think clearly inside it.",
  },
  {
    label: "On Hivemind",
    text:
      "Hivemind is a strategic analytical software company. It exists because the standard tools for strategy work — slide decks, chat threads, ad-hoc memos — are illegible to anyone who did not author them, and barely legible to the author a month later. The premise is unfashionably simple. Strategy is a form of thinking that has to survive being put down and picked up again, by other people, under pressure, often after the conditions that motivated it have shifted. The current toolchain treats this as someone else's problem. Hivemind treats it as the problem. The work is to make analytical thinking durable, in the same plain sense that a well-built house is durable: you can leave it for a while and come back, and it has not collapsed into rubble in your absence.",
  },
  {
    label: "On Purposeless Efficiency",
    text:
      "Purposeless Efficiency is the first volume of a five-book series, and the corresponding written argument to the software work. The thesis, stated as plainly as possible: efficiency severed from purpose has become the dominant production logic of the late industrial era, and that severance has consequences any honest political economy must now treat as central. The book is not a polemic against efficiency. Efficiency, scoped to a real purpose, is one of the small handful of things humans have ever gotten reliably right. The argument is narrower and harder: that we have spent two generations optimizing systems whose purposes were never specified, and have mistaken the optimization itself for evidence that the purposes were sound. They were not. They were assumed. The cost of that assumption is what the book is about.",
  },
  {
    label: "On Theseus",
    text:
      "Theseus is the smallest of the three projects and the most personal. It is a knowledge system for monitoring ideological contradiction — a slow, structured collaborator for the operator-philosopher who wants to know, at any given moment, where their stated commitments contradict themselves. The premise is that the interesting failure mode of a serious thinker is not error in the small but coherence in the large. We tell ourselves stories about what we believe and then live, professionally and politically, in arrangements those stories do not endorse. Theseus is an attempt to make that gap visible to the person who wants to see it. It is not a tool for winning arguments. It is a tool for losing the ones you should lose, on purpose, before someone else makes you lose them by accident.",
  },
  {
    label: "On the working stance",
    text:
      "The working stance, across all of it, is the same. Accuracy over warmth. Rigor over pace. Density over decoration. First principles before citations. Build the interface first and let the content earn its way in. Treat one's own past work as evidence, not identity. None of this is novel. Most of it is older than the disciplines that have lately claimed it. The only thing that is mine, if anything is, is the refusal to let the work get sentimental about itself. A model that cannot be wrong cannot be useful. A book that cannot be argued with is not a book. A piece of software that cannot be questioned by the person using it is not, in any honest sense, a tool.",
  },
];

